title.narrative: OUTPUT 3.1 HEALTH ENABLING ENVIROMENT

description.narrative: By 2024, health sector policy, plans and budgets use solid evidence to strengthen the health system for child and maternal survival., which contributes to Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Communications, Advocacy And Public Engagement, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2024: Significantly more girls, boys, adolescents and women, especially those who are marginalized and/or living in humanitarian conditions, have access to and utilize evidence-based, high-impact quality maternal, neonatal, child, adolescent health, and HIV interventions.

description.narrative: UNICEF contributed to the review and development of several important national health policies and plans, including discussions on supporting costing of the Essential Package of Health Services (EPHS)/Primary Health Care (PHC) documents after validation in 2021. UNICEF also contributed to successful novel OPV vaccine roll-out, with more children vaccinated in the second round. Key 2019/2020 Liberia Demographic and Health Survey (LDHS) reproductive maternal, newborn, child and adolescent health (RMNCAH) data were used for both scorecard development and advocacy and resource mobilization. Emergency-related preparedness and response plans were developed to deliver essential services within the humanitarian-development nexus | Status:On-track | As-of Date:02/02/2022
